Instructions

Read the following passage and answer the questions as directed. There are some blanks given in the passage-based in which some questions are framed, and some words are highlighted as well to help you answer some of the questions.

You probably don't think of your morning cup of tea as a safety hazard. (A)  Still, those ............... leaves can mean injury—even death—for Asian elephants roaming Indian tea gardens, or plantations, in the northeastern state of Assam.

(B) Tea is the second most popular drink in the world (after water), and (1)report in India—the world's second-largest (2)producer behind China—reached a (3)record high of 1.27 million tons in 2016, according to 2018 (4)production by the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations.

(C) Much of the land where tea has grew in Assam is flat, and since stagnant water is terrible for the shrubs, farmers dig drainage trenches to prevent it from accumulating. (D) The trenches are a problem for young elephants, which can fall into them, breaking legs or otherwise ............ themselves and becoming separated from their herds.

Or worse. (E) Kushal Konwar Sarma, a ................ and member of Project Elephant, a government-sponsored wildlife conservation program, says that of the roughly hundred unnatural deaths of elephants a year in Assam—from poisonings to electrocutions—eight to 10 are the result of falls into tea garden trenches.

During the past two decades, veterinarians with the Wildlife Trust of India, a nature conservation organization, have treated 181 calves for various problems, including 42 for trench-related injuries, at the organization's rehabilitation centre in the village of Borjuri. According to N.V. Ashraf Kunhunu, the centre's chief veterinarian, they've succeeded in reuniting only 18 calves with their herds. (F) Those that aren't returned to their families are raised in .......... and eventually, if rehabilitated, are released back into the wild.

(G)(1)Populations of Asian elephants, which are endangered and more at risk than their African (2)authority, are thought to have declined by at least half during the past 75 years, according to the International (3)Union for Conservation of Nature, the global (4)counterparts on the conservation status of species. The most recent estimate, from 2003, but India's wild Asian elephant population at about 30,000. Sarma says Assam has about 5,700 elephants.

(H) According to Lisa Mills, who co-founded Elephant Friendly Tea, an initiative that seeks to identify and encourage consumers to use brands that had took precautions to protect elephants, tea gardens are widespread in parts of the state where the animals live. Elephants almost inevitably have to move through them, Mills says. "I thought—well, this is just a setup for disaster."

(I) Elephants use tea plantations as landmarks when .......... forests, according to Kunhunu. And because there may be fewer people in tea-growing areas, pregnant females often use them as safe havens where they give birth. Their newborns may then be in danger from the trenches.

(J) Kunhunu predicts that the trench problem is only going to get worst because farmers increasingly are growing tea. It's not as labour-intensive as farming rice or corn, and wild animals, including elephants, don't eat the plants, eliminating the need for costly fencing. He says tea gardens now flank the wildlife rehabilitation centre on three sides. "Their numbers are increasing. The percentage of elephant calves getting displaced will be more in the coming years."

Q 1
Report Bookmark

Which of the following word given in the options should come at the place marked as (A) in the above passage to make it grammatically correct and meaningful? Also, the word should fill in the two sentences given below to make them contextually correct and meaningful.
I. Freeze-dried coffee is more ............. than the instant coffee powder and more expensive.
II. No ................ oils, vapour rubs, smelly nasal decongestants like menthol or eucalyptus etc.


Solution


Here, ‘aromatic’ fits best in the blank (A) while reading the sentence and getting its context. It also fits suitably in the given two sentences. Other options are not having relevance with the same. Option (a) is the right answer choice.

Instructions

Read the following passage carefully and answer the questions given below it. Certain words are printed in bold to help you locate them while answering some of the questions.

One can make a pretty good case that while the history of the United States reveals great and enduring innovations in business and industry, one could also argue that U.S. history is a history of war. Depending on one's working definition of war, without doing any research I identify thirteen wars involving the U.S. Our government claims that all of these were not only necessary but also largely forced on us. From my perspective the first one seems a little "iffy," one was definitely forced on us, and at least eleven were actually of our choosing even though our leaders claimed we had no choice.

Almost, without doubt, nearly all Americans would consider that we had no choice but to revolt against England and form a new country. Certainly, the Founders thought so. And perhaps, in the long run, it was inevitable. But were the "facts" at the time so clear that we had to act how and when we did? We all know our Founders' position on the subject, but is it possible that the political class in England also thought that the "facts" obviously justified their position? What was their position in their own eyes?

First, England believed and practised mercantilism at the time. Mercantilism assumes that the home country founded colonies for economic or military advantages for the home country, not especially for the colonists. While the American colonists were English citizens, it was a citizenship that in the eyes of England was a sort of "secondary" citizenship, one that placed the full obligations of citizenship on the American, without "really" providing them with all of the benefits in practice. The position of the colonists at that time was very much like that of Negroes in America, especially in the South, between the end of the Civil War and the 1960s.

The colonists complained about taxes. From England's entirely rational point of view, it had recently spent a great deal of money protecting the colonies during the French and Indian Wars and considered it obvious that the colonies should bear some of the cost, so it enacted taxes to recover part of its war costs. From the colonists' entirely rational point of view, they had fought side by side with the Crown's troops and therefore owed nothing more for their "protection." It was also true that the colonists had no input regarding taxation or much of anything else, and so complained about taxation without representation. While obvious to the colonists, this claimed lack of representation perplexed the government. It was, and still is, a common practice in England for subjects to be represented in Parliament by Members who did not actually live in the districts they represented. Someone somewhere in England was representing the colonists without residing there, so the colonist's claims of taxation without representation had absolutely no merit. As the Crown's total activities proved more and more costly, it levied more taxes on all its subjects, but not necessarily the same taxes on everyone. Thus, the Americans had to pay different taxes while subjects in other parts of the realm may have paid different taxes. Clearly each side thought its positions on the matters entirely logical and proper, and so they were to the respective sides.

The central fact that really mattered much more than bickering over taxes, representation, and so forth is the fact that the needs and desires of the colonists had evolved as the colonies had grown from barely functional outposts of the Empire to self-sustaining, reasonably prosperous enterprises. Their dependence on England had greatly declined in many ways, while their fiscal value to England had finally begun to pay dividends on the investment, time, and even blood the home country had expended on behalf of the colonies. I call the war between the American colonies and England "iffy" because given different attitudes on both sides they could have probably reached a solution to the real problems between them, but independence was probably unavoidable over the longer term. The position on the side of the Americans that they were "forced" into rebellion reflected their emotional involvement as well as legal and economic factors. So I'll stick with "iffy."

What does the word “iffy” mean in the context of the passage?

Credible means believable. Ingenuous means innocent. Lackadaisical means unenthusiastic. Doubtful means which cannot be trusted because of inconsistency. Option A fits best and hence, is the answer.

What was their position in their own eyes?

First, England believed and practised mercantilism at the time. Mercantilism assumes that the home country founded colonies for economic or military advantages for the home country, not especially for the colonists. While the American colonists were English citizens, it was a citizenship that in the eyes of England was a sort of "secondary" citizenship, one that placed the full obligations of citizenship on the American, without "really" providing them with all of the benefits in practice. The position of the colonists at that time was very much like that of Negroes in America, especially in the South, between the end of the Civil War and the 1960s.

The colonists complained about taxes. From England's entirely rational point of view, it had recently spent a great deal of money protecting the colonies during the French and Indian Wars and considered it obvious that the colonies should bear some of the cost, so it enacted taxes to recover part of its war costs. From the colonists' entirely rational point of view, they had fought side by side with the Crown's troops and therefore owed nothing more for their "protection." It was also true that the colonists had no input regarding taxation or much of anything else, and so complained about taxation without representation. While obvious to the colonists, this claimed lack of representation perplexed the government. It was, and still is, a common practice in England for subjects to be represented in Parliament by Members who did not actually live in the districts they represented. Someone somewhere in England was representing the colonists without residing there, so the colonist's claims of taxation without representation had absolutely no merit. As the Crown's total activities proved more and more costly, it levied more taxes on all its subjects, but not necessarily the same taxes on everyone. Thus, the Americans had to pay different taxes while subjects in other parts of the realm may have paid different taxes. Clearly each side thought its positions on the matters entirely logical and proper, and so they were to the respective sides.

The central fact that really mattered much more than bickering over taxes, representation, and so forth is the fact that the needs and desires of the colonists had evolved as the colonies had grown from barely functional outposts of the Empire to self-sustaining, reasonably prosperous enterprises. Their dependence on England had greatly declined in many ways, while their fiscal value to England had finally begun to pay dividends on the investment, time, and even blood the home country had expended on behalf of the colonies. I call the war between the American colonies and England "iffy" because given different attitudes on both sides they could have probably reached a solution to the real problems between them, but independence was probably unavoidable over the longer term. The position on the side of the Americans that they were "forced" into rebellion reflected their emotional involvement as well as legal and economic factors. So I'll stick with "iffy."

Q 77
Report Bookmark

A mixture A contains milk and water in the ratio of 7 : 2. Another mixture B contains milk and water in the ratio of 2 : 1. If A and B are mixed in the ratio of 1 : 3, what is the ratio of milk and water in the final mixture?


Solution

As A and B are mixed in the ratio of 1 : 3, let us assume that 9 litres of A and 27 litres of B are mixed.
In 9 litres of A, milk is 7 litres, and water is 2 litres.
In 27 litres of B, milk is 18 litres, and water is 9 litres.
When A and B are mixed, quantity of milk = (7 + 18) litres = 25 litres
When A and B are mixed, quantity of water = (2 + 9) litres = 11 litres
Required ratio is 25 : 11
Hence, option C is the correct answer.

Q 80
Report Bookmark

A firm has tractors of four models A, B, C and D. Four tractors (two of model B and one each of models C and D) plough a field in 2 days. Two models A tractors and one model C tractor take 3 days to do this job. Three tractors on each of models A, B and C take 4 days to do the same task. How long will it take to do the job if a team is made up of four tractors of different models?


Solution

2/B+1/C+1/D=1/2 …………….(i)
2/A+1/C=1/3………………(ii) and
1/A+1/B+1/C=1/4 ………...(iii)
Subtracting Eq. (i) from Eq. (ii), we get2/A-2/B-1/D=1/6...(iv)
Subtracting Eq. (iii) from Eq. (ii), we get 1/A-1/B=1/12 ⇒2/A-2/B=1/6…………..(v)
Subracting Eq. (v) from Eq. (iv), we get 1/D=1/3 ……….............(vi)
Adding Eqs. (iii) and (iv), we get 1/A+1/B+1/C+1/D=1/4+1/3=7/12
Hence, A, B, C and D will take 12/7 days to do the required job.

Q 81
Report Bookmark

Muthu owns a warehouse that is in the shape of a square. The side of the warehouse is 120 m. He wants to pave the floor of this warehouse with rectangular and triangular tiles. The sides of the triangular tile are 3m, 4m and 5m. The sides of the rectangular tile are 6m and 4m. If he uses only 300 rectangular tiles, what is the minimum number of triangular tiles required?


Solution

Area of the square = 120*120 = 14400 sq.m.
Area of rectangular tile = 6*4 = 24sq.m.
Since Muthu uses 300 tiles, 300*24 = 7200 sq.m will be covered using rectangular tiles.
The triangular tile is of dimensions 3m, 4m and 5m. We can observe that this is a Pythagorean triplet. Hence, this triangle will be exactly half of some rectangular tile. We can fit in 2 triangular tiles to get a rectangular tile of dimension 4m X 3m. Area of one such rectangular tile obtained = 12 sq.m.

7200 sq.m can be covered using 7200/12 = 600 rectangular tiles or 1200 triangular tiles.

Let’s say that Abhinav invests ‘x’ in the first scheme. Hence, he must invest 24000 - x in the second scheme. We have been given the total interest which he earned. So we have
(x(1+.1)2−x)+(24000−x)∗2∗0.12=5256(x(1+.1)^2 - x) + (24000 - x)*2*0.12 = 5256(x(1+.1)2−x)+(24000−x)∗2∗0.12=5256
0.21x + 5760 - .24x = 5256
=> .03x = 504
=> x = 16800

Hence, the percentage will be 7200*100/24000 = 30 %.
Thus, C is the correct answer.

Q 83
Report Bookmark

Akbar and Birbal start a business by investing amounts in the ratio 2:3 respectively. By the end of 6 months, the business yields a profit of Rs. 60,000. The profit is 10% of the total amount invested. Birbal withdraws his investment and profit and quits the business. Akbar reinvests his profit in the business. Chanakya joins the business with an investment of Rs. 3,00,000. If Chanakya’s share in the profit by the end of a year ( 6 months after he joined) is Rs. 1,00,000, what will be Akbar’s share in profit at the same point in time?


Solution

Profit of Rs. 60,000 is 10% of the amount invested.
=> Amount invested = Rs, 6,00,000.
Akbar’s investment = Rs. 2,40,000
Birbal’s investment = Rs. 3,60,000.
After 6 months, Birbal would have withdrawn Rs. 3,60,000 and his profit share of Rs. 36,000.
Therefore, Akbar would have been left with Rs. 2,40,000 + Rs. 24,000 = Rs.2,64,000.
By the end of 6 months, Akbar’s and Chanakya’s share of profits will be in the ratio of their investments 2,64,000: 3,00,000 = 22:25.

Let 'x' be the total profit to be shared between Akbar and Chanakya.
If Chanakya’s share is Rs. 1,00,000.
(25/(25+22))*x = 1,00,000
x = 1,88,000
Total Profit - Chanakya’s share = Akbar's Share
1,88,000 - 1,00,000 =88,000
Akbar’s share must be Rs. 88,000.

Q 84
Report Bookmark

A shopkeeper marks up the goods by 100 percent. He sells it at a certain discount and still earns a profit of 25 percent. Now the cost price of the good comes down by 25 percent but the shopkeeper continues to keep the same marked price and discount. What will be his profit under the new conditions?


Solution

Let the CP of the product be 100.
Hence, the marked price will be 200 and SP will be 125. Now the marked price comes down by 25 percent. Hence, the new marked price will be 100*.75 = 75
The selling price is still 125. Hence, the required profit percentage will be
(125 - 75)*100/75 = 66.67%

What is the difference between the number of students who passed in Paper-III in Class C and the number of students who passed in Paper-I in Class A?

Total number of students = 700

Number of students in Class B = 34% of 700 = 238

19x+9x = 196
28x = 196
x = 7

Number of students in D = 9x = 9*7 = 63

14x = 238
x = 17
Then, Number of students who passed in Paper I of B = 5x = 5*17 = 85
Number of students who passed in Paper II of B = 2x = 2*17 = 34

Number of students who passed in Paper I of C = 42.84% of 133 = 37×133=57\dfrac{3}{7}\times133 = 5773​×133=57
Number of students who passed in Paper II of C = 28.56% of 133 = 27×133=38\dfrac{2}{7}\times133 = 3872​×133=38

Let the number of students who passed in Paper II of D be x

Q 126

Which of the following sets of symbols should replace the question marks in the given expression in that order (from left to right), in order to make the expressions ‘S > O’ and ‘D < C’ definitely false?
S ? E ? C ? O ? N ? D


Solution

The set of symbols ‘≤, <, =, <, <’ should replace the questions marks in the given expression in that order in order to make the expression ‘S > O’ and D < C’ definitely false. Then the expression becomes, ‘S ≤ E < C = O < N < D’. Choice b

The Minister said that the government had sought the Commission’s permission to appoint the army chief as it wanted to strictly follow all the procedures.

Which of the following can be inferred from the above?


Solution

The statement did not make any reference to the elections. Hence, a cannot be inferred. The statement refers to the appointment of army chief only and not to any other appointment. Hence, neither b nor e can be inferred. The commission’s response cannot be inferred from the information available. Hence, c cannot be inferred. Q 128
Report Bookmark

Which of the following means Q is the aunt of P?


Solution

Q @ R - P ==> Q is the sister of R. And R is the father of P. ==> Q is the aunt of P.

P@R -Q ==> P is the sister of R, R is the father of Q. ==> P is the aunt of Q.

P - R * Q ==> P is the father of R, R is the brother of Q ==> P is the father of Q.

P * R $ Q ==> P is the brother of R, R is the mother of Q ==> P is the uncle of Q.

Therefore only option A agrees with the given condition.

Q 138
Report Bookmark

Read the following information carefully and answer the question that follows.

A one year moratorium is imposed by University Grants Commission (UGC) on setting up new engineering colleges and increasing the intake in engineering colleges as the number of engineering jobs created in the country is much lower than the number of engineers passing out from colleges.

Which of the following is the fallacy in the decision taken by the UGC?


Solution

The UGC has taken a decision to restrict number of engineering colleges and the number of engineering graduates. The reason cited for this decision is that there is not employment opportunities available to engineers. It is a failure on the part of the government to create employment opportunities and not a mistake of engineering graduates. Moreover, the government has the responsibility to provide opportunity to pursue any course one wishes to. Hence, Choice b is the fallacy in the decision taken by the UGC. Choice a states that private institutes are ready to establish engineering colleges, this information does not go against the decision UGC. Hence, a is not a fallacy. Choice c states the preference of the recruiters but does not state how many people are they willing to recruit. Hence, c is not a fallacy. Choice d states that employment opportunities are available in foreign countries. There is no information regarding the willingness of people going to abroad to grab this opportunity. Hence, d is not a fallacy. Choice e supports the decision taken by UGC. Thus b is the fallacy in the decision taken by UGC. Choice b

Study the following instructions and answer the questions that follow:

Eight members A, B, C, D, E, F, G and H belong to a family which is spread across three generations. There are three couples in the family. No one in the third generations are married. They are travelling in a train in eight berths which are numbered from 25 to 32 such that each person travels in each berth. They have different ages. The person who was born in 1967 was allotted berth number which is 2 more than half of his age. F has only two children. H’s berth is next to that of C. B is 18 years older than her son and 3 years older than her brother. H has no siblings. The age of A is double the berth number of E while the age of G is half of the berth number of H. The granddaughter of A was born in 2003. The brother-in-law of D was born in 1976. D was born in 1985 and his berth number is four less than his age. A is mother-in-law of C. The husband of A is four years older than her. A was born in 1967 but she is not the eldest in the family. The berth number of the person who was born in 1963 was not 27. B’s son is younger than D’s wife. Four persons are there between the berths of B and her brother. C’s daughter is 13 years younger than C and is the youngest person in the family. E is nephew of D. H has only one child. C has only one daughter. Only two persons are younger than C who is sister-in-law of B. B is the sister of D.

Q 139
Report Bookmark

How many persons are younger than F?


Solution

A was born in 1967 but she is not the eldest in the family. The age of A is double the berth number of E.
Here, The age of A is 52. Then the berth number of E is 26.
B is the sister of D. C is sister-in-law of B. A is mother-in-law of C. Hence, B, C and D cannot be in third generation and first generation since A is in upper generation of them.
Four persons are there between the berths of B and her brother. F has only two children. H has only one child. Here, Three couples in the family will be B and her husband, D and his wife, A and F.
E is nephew of D. C has only one daughter. Remaining person is G who is C’s daughter.  H has no siblings.

Therefore, Final blood relation will be as shown above.

D was born in 1985 and his berth number is four less than his age. Age of D is 34 and berth number of D is 30.

The person who was born in 1967 was allotted berth number which is 2 more than half of his age. A’s age is 52 and A’s berth number is (52/2)+2 = 28.

Four persons are there between the berths of B and her brother. Here, D is B’s brother. B is 18 years older than her son and 3 years older than her brother. Hence, B’s age is 37 and her son E’s age is 19.

The husband of A is four years older than her. Hence, F’s age is 56.

The brother-in-law of D was born in 1976. Here, H is D’s brother-in-law.

C’s daughter is 13 years younger than C and is the youngest person in the family. The granddaughter of A was born in 2003. Hence, G was born in 2003 and C was born in 1990. H’s berth is next to that of C. The age of G is half of the berth number of H.

The berth number of the person who was born in 1963 was not 27. Here, F’s berth will be 29 and G’s berth will be 27.

Therefore, The final arrangement is as shown above.

Here, F is the oldest person in the family. Hence, 7 persons are younger than F.

Instructions

Eight friends A, B, C, D, E, F, G and H are born in the same year. Their dates of birth are 13th of January, 21st of January, 13th of February, 21st of February, 13th of March, 21st of March, 13th of April and 21st of April. Further, the following information is known about them.

Q 166
Report Bookmark

Who celebrates his birthday 21st of February?


Solution

A and G share the same date while A and D share the same month of birth. A is older than D. Therefore, A must be born on 13th of a month, D must be born on 21st of the same month and G must be born on 13th of a different month.

D and B share the same date of birth. Therefore, B must be born on 21st of some month. At least 3 persons celebrate their birthdays between A and B. This statement implies that B must be born on either 21st of March or 21st of April. Since B is not the youngest person, B must be born on 21st of March.

Since at least 3 persons celebrate their birthday between A and B, A must be born on 13th of January.

G and B do not share the same month of birth. Therefore, G can be born on April or February. G and B do not share the same date of birth. Therefore, G must be born on 13th of a month. H is older than G. Since January is already taken up by A-D pair, H must be born on February and G must be born on 13th of April.

F and H share the same month of birth and H is younger than F. Therefore, F must be born on 13th of February and H must be born on 21st of February.

Hence, the final arrangement is as follows:

H celebrates his birthday on 21st of February. Therefore, option D is the right answer.

Q 196
Report Bookmark

Which of the statements (A), (B), (C), (D), (E), (F) and (G) is/are point(s) that goes against making voting compulsory?


Solution

Statement (A) talks about what happens when there is a low voter turnout, which is not desirable. Hence, (A) is a possible reason why the point is raised.
Statement (B) talks about the effect of not casting vote.
Statement (C) is what those who ask to make voting compulsory believe. If the belief is that it is not possible, then there would not have been a discussion about making voting compulsory. Hence, (C) is an assumption of those asking for such step.
Statement (D) talks about a measure that would force people to cat vote.
Statement (E) provides a possible reason for low voter turnout.
Statement (F) is also an assumption of those asking for making voting compulsory. In asking for such measure the point that someone may have very genuine reasons for not being able to cast their vote, is not being considered. This indicates that they are under the assumption that every voter will be able to cast vote. Hence, (F) is an assumption.
Statement (G) raises a point which opposes the measure to make voting compulsory.
Statement (G) is a point that goes against the suggested measure. Choice b
